{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set deg = card_data.degradation_table %}
{% set headline = card_data.headline %}
{% set comparison = card_data.tier_comparison %}
{% set comparison_short = comparison.rows[0] %}
{% set comparison_long = comparison.rows[1] %}
{% set alpha_r = deg.alpha_estimation.R %}
{% set alpha_e = deg.alpha_estimation.E %}
{% set false_attribution = headline.r_tier_false_attribution %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/x1.css?v={{ asset_version }}">
{% endblock %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="atlas-intro">
  <p class="atlas-headline">
    How much evidence is needed before an alpha signal is reliable?
    <strong>Measured exposures cross the {{ "%.0f"|format(comparison.target_power * 100) }}% detection threshold at {{ comparison_long.months }} months</strong>,
    reaching {{ "%.1f"|format(comparison_long.measured_exposure.power * 100) }}%.
    Returns alone reach {{ "%.1f"|format(comparison_long.returns_only.power * 100) }}%, but their
    Wilson interval still crosses the threshold. The richer evidence improves detectability; it
    does not make the simulation result exact.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="x1-tier-comparison" aria-labelledby="x1-tier-comparison-title">
  <div class="x1-tier-comparison__heading">
    <div>
      <p class="x1-tier-comparison__eyebrow">Main comparison</p>
      <h2 id="x1-tier-comparison-title">What measured exposures add at four and ten years</h2>
    </div>
    <p>Posterior detection probability at one fixed synthetic effect
      (information coefficient {{ "%.2f"|format(comparison.effect_ic) }}, realized information ratio
      {{ "%.2f"|format(comparison.effect_realized_ir) }}).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="x1-tier-chart-frame">
    <span class="x1-tier-axis x1-tier-axis--y">Detection probability</span>
    <div class="x1-tier-chart-area">
      <span class="x1-tier-threshold-label">{{ "%.0f"|format(comparison.target_power * 100) }}% reliability threshold</span>
      <svg class="x1-tier-chart" viewBox="0 0 420 250" role="img"
           aria-label="Returns-only and measured-exposure posterior detection probabilities at 48 and 120 months"
           data-target="{{ comparison.target_power }}"
           data-months="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='months') | join(',') }}"
           data-returns="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='returns_only.power') | join(',') }}"
           data-returns-lo="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='returns_only.wilson.lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-returns-hi="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='returns_only.wilson.hi') | join(',') }}"
           data-exposure="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='measured_exposure.power') | join(',') }}"
           data-exposure-lo="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='measured_exposure.wilson.lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-exposure-hi="{{ comparison.rows | map(attribute='measured_exposure.wilson.hi') | join(',') }}"></svg>
      <div class="x1-tier-y-labels" aria-hidden="true"><span>100%</span><span>80%</span><span>0%</span></div>
    </div>
    <span class="x1-tier-axis x1-tier-axis--x">Track length (months)</span>
  </div>
  <div class="x1-tier-comparison__results">
    {% for row in comparison.rows %}
    <article>
      <h3>{{ row.months }} months</h3>
      <p><strong>Returns only:</strong> {{ "%.1f"|format(row.returns_only.power * 100) }}%
        <span>Wilson 95% interval {{ "%.1f"|format(row.returns_only.wilson.lo * 100) }}%&ndash;{{ "%.1f"|format(row.returns_only.wilson.hi * 100) }}%</span></p>
      <p><strong>Measured exposures:</strong> {{ "%.1f"|format(row.measured_exposure.power * 100) }}%
        <span>Wilson 95% interval {{ "%.1f"|format(row.measured_exposure.wilson.lo * 100) }}%&ndash;{{ "%.1f"|format(row.measured_exposure.wilson.hi * 100) }}%</span></p>
    </article>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  <p class="x1-tier-comparison__takeaway">At {{ comparison_long.months }} months, the
    <strong>returns-only interval spans the {{ "%.0f"|format(comparison.target_power * 100) }}% threshold</strong>.
    The measured-exposure point is above it, but its own interval remains visible because simulation
    power is estimated rather than known.</p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <p class="tearsheet-note"><strong>What you are looking at.</strong>
  The opening comparison asks how much measured exposures improve detection at the same
  synthetic skill level and track length. The later curves ask how many months of track record a
  returns-only skill test needs at three known skill levels (realized information ratio, or IR,
  {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[0].realized_ir) }}, {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[1].realized_ir) }}, and {{ "%.2f"|format(card_data.power_curves[2].realized_ir) }}). The
  cohort-informed shrinkage posterior climbs fastest but still tops out just below
  the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% reliability threshold at the middle effect
  ({{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.power * 100) }}% at {{ headline.reference.max_months }} months).
  Its Wilson 95% interval is
  {{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.wilson.lo * 100) }}%&ndash;{{ "%.1f"|format(headline.r_tier.wilson.hi * 100) }}%,
  which spans the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% threshold; the current rule remains based on the {{ "%.3f"|format(headline.r_tier.power) }} point estimate.
  It fires {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% of the
  time when there is no skill at all (its information coefficient, or IC, is {{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }} at {{ false_attribution.months }} months). Measuring betas through
  exposure summaries is what pushes the posterior point over the threshold within a {{ headline.reference.max_months // 12 }}-year record.
  The later table reads a frequentist alpha test at {{ deg.T }} months and information coefficient
  {{ "%.2f"|format(deg.ic) }}: power rises from {{ "%.1f"|format(alpha_r.power * 100) }}% with returns only to {{ "%.1f"|format(alpha_e.power * 100) }}% with
  measured exposures. Every number is {{ card_data.meta.n_reps }}-manager simulator output, illustrative
  and uncalibrated.</p>
  <p class="tearsheet-note"><strong>How to read it.</strong></p>
  <ul class="tearsheet-note">
    <li><strong>Two lines per panel</strong> &mdash; the ordinary least squares (OLS) <em>t</em>-test and the
    shrinkage posterior, plotted as detection rate (power) against sample length
    <em>T</em> in months.</li>
    <li><strong>Dashed horizontal line</strong> &mdash; the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power bar; where a
    curve crosses it is the tenure at which that metric becomes reliable.</li>
    <li><strong>Amber poster label</strong> &mdash; the posterior's false-alarm price
    ({{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }}), the cost of borrowing strength across a cohort.</li>
    <li><strong>Evidence comparison</strong> &mdash; the gap between returns only and measured
      exposures shows what additional visibility buys for this specific test.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="tearsheet-note">The full methodology &mdash; with the math and a reference
  implementation &mdash; is in the
  <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">technical method</a>.</p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">Further analysis &mdash; how the true effect changes the power curve</h2>
  <p class="atlas-poster-label">
    cohort-informed; {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }} &mdash; the price of borrowing strength
  </p>
  <div class="atlas-curves">
    {% for curve in card_data.power_curves %}
    <figure class="atlas-curve">
      <svg class="x1-powercurve" viewBox="0 0 100 44" preserveAspectRatio="none"
           role="img" aria-label="Power vs sample length"
           data-t="{{ curve.T | join(',') }}"
           data-ols="{{ curve.ols_ttest | join(',') }}"
           data-ols-lo="{{ curve.ols_ttest_wilson | map(attribute='lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-ols-hi="{{ curve.ols_ttest_wilson | map(attribute='hi') | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior="{{ curve.posterior | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior-lo="{{ curve.posterior_wilson | map(attribute='lo') | join(',') }}"
           data-posterior-hi="{{ curve.posterior_wilson | map(attribute='hi') | join(',') }}"></svg>
      <figcaption class="atlas-curve__cap">
        realized IR {{ "%.2f"|format(curve.realized_ir) }}
        <span class="atlas-curve__legend">
          <span class="atlas-legend atlas-legend--ols">OLS t-test</span>
          <span class="atlas-legend atlas-legend--posterior">posterior</span>
        </span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
  <p class="tearsheet-note">Dashed line marks the {{ "%.0f"|format(headline.reference.target_power * 100) }}% power threshold; x-axis is track length in months,
  {{ card_data.power_curves[0].T[0] }} to {{ card_data.power_curves[0].T[-1] }}. Shaded envelopes show Wilson 95% intervals.</p>
</section>

<section class="tearsheet-panel">
  <h2 class="tearsheet-panel__title">Supporting comparison at {{ deg.T }} months</h2>
  <table class="atlas-degradation">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Analytic</th><th>Evidence available</th><th>Power</th><th>Monte Carlo uncertainty</th><th>RMSE</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Alpha estimation</td><td>Returns only</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>{{ "%.4f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.R.rmse) }}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Alpha estimation</td><td>Measured exposures</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>{{ "%.4f"|format(deg.alpha_estimation.E.rmse) }}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hit rate</td><td>Positions and trades</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.hit_rate_P.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.hit_rate_P.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sizing skill</td><td>Positions and trades</td><td>{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.sizing_skill_P.power * 100) }}%</td><td>Wilson 95% &plusmn;{{ "%.1f"|format(deg.sizing_skill_P.wilson.half_width * 100) }} pp</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Drift detection</td><td>Measured exposures versus returns only</td><td colspan="3">{{ deg.drift_detection }}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The simulator emits returns, exposure summaries, and positions and trades from the
same known ground truth, so every metric is scored against the truth at every evidence
level and sample size. Power =
P(detect | effect present); size = P(detect | IC = 0); the IC=0 column is the
false-alarm rate, not filler. Each power number carries its own Wilson 95%
half-width (this demonstration runs 500 managers per cell; the publication threshold
requires at least 1,000).</p>
<p>The shrinkage posterior borrows strength across a strategy cohort, buying power at
short tenures &mdash; at the cost of {{ "%.1f"|format(false_attribution.power * 100) }}% false-attribution at IC={{ "%g"|format(false_attribution.ic) }}. That is the price
of borrowing strength, stated plainly rather than hidden.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/x1-atlas.js?v={{ asset_version }}"></script>
{% endblock %}
